        "https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.13491",
        "https://arxiv.org/html/2510.09734",
        "https://distill.pub/2020/growing-ca/",
        "https://arxiv.org/html/2505.13058v1",
        "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11078362/",
        "https://huggingface.co/blog/moe"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "rq-1739254800004-nca-model-zoos",
      "topic": "NCA model zoos with learned routers - can collections of specialized NCAs approximate foundation model behavior?",
      "source": "Research follow-up from NCA pretraining study",
      "addedBy": "research-agent",
      "addedAt": "2026-02-13T08:00:00Z",
      "completedAt": "2026-02-14T23:45:00Z",
      "priority": 6,
      "tags": [
        "neural-networks",
        "mixture-of-experts",
        "routing",
        "nca"
      ],
      "summary": "Collections of specialized NCAs with learned routing represent a pragmatic alternative to foundation models. Three architectural paradigms: genomic signal encoding (2-8+ textures from single NCA), mixture-of-NCAs (probabilistic per-cell rule routing), and attention-based universal NCAs. RouteLLM-style learned routers can achieve 60-63% compute reduction by directing queries to appropriate specialists. Model zoo approach better suited to NCAs' local computation paradigm than pursuing single foundation models\u2014extreme parameter efficiency (68-8000 params) makes training large collections trivial. Critical open questions: optimal routing granularity, load balancing in spatial domains, whether local computation can achieve global reasoning.",
      "sources": [
        "https://arxiv.org/html/2506.20486",
        "https://arxiv.org/html/2505.13058v1",
        "https://arxiv.org/html/2407.05991v2",
        "https://huggingface.co/blog/moe",
        "https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.18665",
        "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-025-23997-7",
        "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11078362/",
        "https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/neural-cellular-automata-nca",
        "https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.11131",
        "https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.22899",
        "https://arxiv.org/html/2510.00742v3",
        "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41551-025-01516-3",
        "https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10462-024-11058-w",
        "https://github.com/lm-sys/RouteLLM",
        "https://friendli.ai/blog/moe-models-comparison"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "rq-1739254800003-nca-scaling-laws",
      "topic": "Scaling laws for NCAs - relationships between parameter count, training compute, pattern complexity, and generalization",
      "source": "Research follow-up from NCA pretraining study",
      "addedBy": "research-agent",
      "addedAt": "2026-02-13T08:00:00Z",
      "priority": 6,
      "tags": [
        "neural-networks",
        "scaling-laws",
        "performance-analysis",
        "nca"
      ],
      "completedAt": "2026-02-14T23:30:00Z",
      "summary": "NCAs exhibit fundamentally different scaling than transformers: parameter efficiency through iterative computation (68-8000 params sufficient for many tasks), quadratic O(H\u00b2\u00d7W\u00b2) compute scaling with resolution, channel count as primary model size metric, and generalization via learned dynamics rather than overparameterization. Unlike Kaplan/Chinchilla power laws, NCA capacity = parameters \u00d7 iterations \u00d7 receptive field. Key findings: Diff-NCA (336k params) outperforms 4\u00d7 larger UNet; ViTCA achieves linear complexity through CA iteration amortization; architectural innovations (attention, hierarchy) address resolution bottleneck. Missing: systematic empirical studies across parameter scales, compute-optimal iteration budgets, predictive scaling equations.",
      "sources": [
        "https://www.nature.com/articles/s44335-025-00026-4",
        "https://arxiv.org/html/2506.22899v2",
        "https://arxiv.org/abs/2111.13545",
        "https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.01233",
        "https://arxiv.org/html/2406.08298",
        "https://distill.pub/2020/growing-ca/",
        "https://dynca.github.io/",
        "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_scaling_law",
        "https://arxiv.org/abs/2001.08361",
        "https://lifearchitect.ai/chinchilla/",
        "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11078362/",
        "https://arxiv.org/html/2410.02651v1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "rq-1739254800002-hierarchical-nca",
      "topic": "Hierarchical multi-scale NCAs with cross-scale communication - can they achieve foundation model capabilities?",
      "source": "Research follow-up from NCA pretraining study",
      "addedBy": "research-agent",
      "addedAt": "2026-02-13T08:00:00Z",
      "completedAt": "2026-02-14T22:00:00Z",
      "priority": 7,
      "tags": [
        "neural-networks",
        "hierarchical-models",
        "multi-scale",
        "architecture",
        "nca"
      ],
      "summary": "Hierarchical multi-scale NCAs address fundamental NCA limitations through three paradigms: explicit hierarchy (HNCA, hGCA with parent-child communication), attention-based hierarchy (ViTCA with localized self-attention), and hybrid architectures (AdaNCA as ViT adaptors). While true foundation NCAs don't exist yet, hierarchical designs achieve transfer learning and robustness with extreme parameter efficiency. Path to foundation capabilities: self-supervised pre-training + CLIP conditioning + model zoos with learned routers. Critical open question: can local computation paradigm achieve global reasoning abilities?",
      "sources": [
        "https://direct.mit.edu/isal/proceedings-pdf/isal2023/35/20/2354957/isal_a_00601.pdf",
